    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "This is a good question. What we want to distinguish is not so much the\ntransport but the semantics of trust validation in TLS (which is silent\nabout any given trust model). HTTPS is typically what we refer to for\nserver host name validation as it references something that the industry\nunderstands.\n`TlsWithServerHostNameValidation` would be a bit sad. Another solution\nwould be to keep TLS and add options for a given trust model where Server\nHost Name validation would be the default.\n\nOn Wed, Dec 13, 2017 at 3:50 PM, Mehrdad Afshari <notifications@github.com>\nwrote:\n\n> @jboeuf <https://github.com/jboeuf> I see... would HTTPS still be a good\n> name considering we potentially run on non-HTTP2 transports?\n>\n> —\n> You are receiving this because you were mentioned.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/grpc/grpc/issues/13481#issuecomment-351562752>, or mute\n> the thread\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AF-P7UTiqYvGla93Pn_Pijw7imLgGYuyks5tAGLMgaJpZM4QmXTr>\n> .\n>\n"
  },
